00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.083
and I want to think about
what Thanksgiving means,

00:01:14.083 --> 00:01:21.530
and what it feels like, and the
things around Thanksgiving that

00:01:21.530 --> 00:01:25.150
give us some insight into
cooperation and competition.

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:27.300
Our book "Friend and Foe"
is about this duality

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:30.710
where we're both cooperating
and competing with people.

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:32.950
And Thanksgiving is this
quintessentially cooperative

00:01:32.950 --> 00:01:33.450
holiday.

00:01:33.450 --> 00:01:34.860
We get together with family.

00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:37.620
We celebrate the
history of cooperation.

00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:39.120
And if there's
something else that's

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:42.840
funny about Thanksgiving,
along with Thanksgiving,

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:44.640
we've now come to
associate Thanksgiving

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:49.410
with the start of the holiday
season, where we often

00:01:49.410 --> 00:01:54.030
see great sales that
start that evening,

00:01:54.030 --> 00:01:57.110
or very early morning
of the next day.

00:01:57.110 --> 00:02:01.140
So we go from Thanksgiving,
often having this meal.

00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:03.750
And depending on where
you live, or how you shop,

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:07.300
people often go from
dinner to the mall.

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:09.180
And I'll tell you about
one mall experience

00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:11.270
that happened in 2008.

00:02:11.270 --> 00:02:18.790
Since 2008, we'll see
people gather at a store.

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:21.860
The story I want to tell
you about is about Walmart

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:25.150
in 2008 in White
Marsh, where there

00:02:25.150 --> 00:02:28.150
was a sale that was happening
at 5:00 in the morning.

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:30.710
And people had gathered
outside that store

00:02:30.710 --> 00:02:35.080
to get discounted prices on
things like TVs and so on.

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:38.040
And there were so many
people, that the staff

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:40.471
called the police to try
to help control this crowd.

00:02:40.471 --> 00:02:41.970
The police had shown
up, but weren't

00:02:41.970 --> 00:02:44.300
able to actually do very much.

00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:49.200
The crowd had posted a sign that
read, blitz line starts here.

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:53.317
And they started chanting
tear the doors down.

00:02:53.317 --> 00:02:54.400
They're chanting this way.

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.970
The employees of the
Walmart formed a human chain

00:02:57.970 --> 00:03:00.300
to try to control the crowd.

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:01.820
The crowd rushed in.

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:05.990
They literally took the doors
off the hinges as they came in.

00:03:05.990 --> 00:03:07.770
They ended up trampling people.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:10.590
And Damour here ended up
getting trampled to death.

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:13.610
Somebody who had just
celebrated Thanksgiving

00:03:13.610 --> 00:03:18.804
ended up being the
victim of this mob.

00:03:18.804 --> 00:03:20.220
What we want to
think about is how

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:24.630
we shift from cooperation
and competition and back,

00:03:24.630 --> 00:03:28.350
and how we find our balance
as we cooperate and compete.

00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:32.050
So our book it talks
about cooperation.

00:03:32.050 --> 00:03:34.750
So you think about
parents raising an infant.

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:38.680
They're cooperating at this
intimate, incredible level.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:41.620
And even as they're the
quintessential cooperators,

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:44.790
they're also competing,
often in that same domain,

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.720
for things like who
gets to sleep in,

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:48.120
who changes the diaper.

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.540
We're often cooperating
and competing, even

00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:53.470
with the people very,
very, very close to us.

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:55.720
Now it's not just parents.

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:56.910
You think about siblings.

00:03:56.910 --> 00:03:59.480
What could be better
than brotherly love?

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:00.960
But also sort of
quintessentially,

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:02.160
we have sibling rivalry.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:07.410
That is sometimes, the
people very close to us

00:04:07.410 --> 00:04:10.970
are also ones with whom
we most intensely compete.

00:04:10.970 --> 00:04:13.940
And we might compete for things
like financial resources,

00:04:13.940 --> 00:04:15.919
but also things like
anything that's scarce,

00:04:15.919 --> 00:04:18.550
like parental
attention, and so on.

00:04:18.550 --> 00:04:21.410
And there's a very
special relationship

00:04:21.410 --> 00:04:24.930
that I'll come back
to, and that's twins.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:27.500
And for twins, this idea of
cooperation and competition

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.210
starts quite early.

00:04:29.210 --> 00:04:30.950
For twins, it starts
before they're born.

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:33.720
Actually, in the womb, they're
both cooperating and competing

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:36.010
for resources.

00:04:36.010 --> 00:04:38.300
In fact, we were
talking recently,

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:43.570
and somebody told us about when
they're watching the twins,

00:04:43.570 --> 00:04:46.510
one of the twins was
kicking the other one.

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:50.500
You sort of see that the
competition start really early.

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:53.220
Now, at work, we
need to collaborate.

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:55.520
And so one of our
challenges is to figure out,

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:57.880
how do things like
share knowledge,

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:00.480
collaborate as a group.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:02.950
So we're collaborating,
but at the same time,

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:06.250
once or as we're going
through that, we also

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:08.300
need to balance competition.

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:09.490
Who's going to get credit?

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:11.290
Who's going to get promoted?

00:05:11.290 --> 00:05:13.080
Who's going to get a raise?

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:15.410
So we're both
collaborating and competing

00:05:15.410 --> 00:05:17.580
in order to find our balance.

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:20.390
So essential theme
of our book is

00:05:20.390 --> 00:05:24.300
that we're cooperating and
competing all the time, often

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:26.040
with the same people.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:28.787
And we need to find our
balance as we do this.

00:05:28.787 --> 00:05:30.370
And so what we'll
do is we'll take you

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:33.230
through a couple of ideas
about the constructs

00:05:33.230 --> 00:05:36.660
that we consider that shift
us between cooperation

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:40.440
and competition and back.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:42.560
So we're looking to
find our balance.

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:44.610
We could cooperate too much.

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:48.090
We might make ourselves too
vulnerable to exploitation.

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:50.330
We could try somebody
too much, and end up

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:51.520
getting burned by it.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:53.104
But if we compete
too much, we're

00:05:53.104 --> 00:05:54.520
going to miss out
on opportunities

00:05:54.520 --> 00:05:57.070
to collaborate,
and expand the pie,

00:05:57.070 --> 00:05:59.886
and end up moving
a team forward.

00:05:59.886 --> 00:06:01.260
But if we find
the right balance,

00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:05.130
we'll end up doing
the very best.

00:06:05.130 --> 00:06:06.690
Here's the first idea.

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:08.700
When we think about
comparison, so

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:12.640
if we think about things like,
do you make a good salary?

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:14.411
Do you need to
update your kitchen?

00:06:14.411 --> 00:06:15.410
Do you drive a nice car?

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:20.520
Is my workspace adequate?

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:22.170
How are my kids doing?

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:23.760
All of those
judgments are really

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.700
hard to assess in the abstract.

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:29.560
And instead, we make
these relative judgements.

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:32.570
So as we're looking for
comparisons, as our mind

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:35.500
almost instinctively
races to comparisons,

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:37.750
there's some individual
differences that some of us

00:06:37.750 --> 00:06:39.315
do this more than others.

00:06:39.315 --> 00:06:41.190
But we're constantly
scanning our environment

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:43.370
to figure out, hey,
how am I doing?

00:06:43.370 --> 00:06:45.260
How are my kids doing?

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:47.190
What do I need?

00:06:47.190 --> 00:06:48.570
And we make these comparisons.

00:06:48.570 --> 00:06:49.660
We might check Facebook.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:51.860
We might ask other people.

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:53.770
We might try to
figure out what's

00:06:53.770 --> 00:06:59.050
going on to the other
people's kids around us.

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:01.510
So it could be that our
kids are playing soccer,

00:07:01.510 --> 00:07:06.801
and they're young, nobody keeps
score, except for the parents.

00:07:06.801 --> 00:07:08.050
The parents are keeping score.

00:07:08.050 --> 00:07:09.760
They know who scored the goals.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:12.260
They know which team is winning.

00:07:12.260 --> 00:07:15.180
And so here, we're
instinctively hard wired

00:07:15.180 --> 00:07:17.890
to make these comparisons.

00:07:17.890 --> 00:07:20.270
Larry Bird and Magic
Johnson, for example,

00:07:20.270 --> 00:07:22.390
had a very special
competitive relationship.

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:25.370
The special
relationship is rivalry.

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:27.890
When we have rivals, it's
a really intense form

00:07:27.890 --> 00:07:29.810
of competition.

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:31.762
And here, Larry
Bird talks about,

00:07:31.762 --> 00:07:33.470
"The first thing I
would do every morning

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:36.330
was look at the box scores."

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:38.970
He wanted to see what
Magic did, and that to

00:07:38.970 --> 00:07:41.480
him was the most
important thing.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:43.230
Now, here's what's
good about comparisons.

00:07:43.230 --> 00:07:45.990
Comparisons can be
powerfully motivating.

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:47.890
We see something.

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:50.080
We're comparing ourselves
with somebody else.

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:51.880
And we're motivated
by that, and that

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:53.540
can be really constructive.

00:07:53.540 --> 00:07:56.960
So there's a very healthy
component to this.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:58.720
So here's the good
in comparisons.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:02.190
It increases motivation,
can boost performance,

00:08:02.190 --> 00:08:04.590
and if we can harness
cooperation in the right way,

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:07.090
it can be very good.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:10.750
But there's some problems
with comparisons also.

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.790
And comparisons can make
us not only more motivated,

00:08:13.790 --> 00:08:16.810
but can make us
perfectly miserable.

00:08:16.810 --> 00:08:18.800
And I suggest that these
are really hard-wired.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:22.260
And I'll show you a short video
about how hard-wired they are.

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:26.560
This is a study that Frans de
Waal did with Capuchin monkeys.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:28.430
These monkeys are
really quite clever,

00:08:28.430 --> 00:08:33.450
and he taught them how to use
stones as a type of money.

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:35.400
So they would use these stones.

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:38.740
They'd hand them to the
experimenter, and in exchange

00:08:38.740 --> 00:08:39.425
get some reward.

00:08:42.090 --> 00:08:43.620
Now here's what
we're going to see.

00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:46.030
We're going to see a video
of two Capuchin monkeys side

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:47.770
by side.

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:48.870
They both have stones.

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:51.080
They're going to hand the
stone to the experimenter,

00:08:51.080 --> 00:08:53.010
and they're going
to get something.

00:08:53.010 --> 00:08:57.320
In one cage, one monkey's
going to get cucumbers.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:08:59.330
And you can do
this with monkeys,

00:08:59.330 --> 00:09:00.570
and they'll do this all day.

00:09:00.570 --> 00:09:02.640
They like to eat cucumbers.

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:04.660
It's easy enough to
hand the stones over,

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:07.170
and they'll keep
getting these cucumbers.

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:08.760
The experiment he
did, however, he

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:12.350
put another monkey in the
cage next to that monkey.

00:09:12.350 --> 00:09:16.720
And that other monkey, when they
give the stone, got a grape.

00:09:16.720 --> 00:09:19.230
Now, the grape's much
better than a cucumber.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:20.887
And you'll see what happens.

00:09:20.887 --> 00:09:21.590
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:22.590
-She gives a rock to us.

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:24.600
That's the task.

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:26.900
And you give her a piece
of cucumber, and she eats.

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:29.566
The other one needs
to give a rock to us.

00:09:29.566 --> 00:09:31.906
And that's what she does.

00:09:31.906 --> 00:09:35.189
And she gets a grape.

00:09:35.189 --> 00:09:37.161
And see, the other
one sees that.

00:09:37.161 --> 00:09:40.612
And she gives a rock to
us and gets a cucumber.

00:09:44.556 --> 00:09:48.007
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:48.007 --> 00:09:49.944
[END PLAYBACK]

00:09:49.944 --> 00:09:51.360
MAURICE SCHWEITZER:
And so what it

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:55.970
suggests is that is a
stone worth a cucumber?

00:09:55.970 --> 00:09:59.330
Well, it is until somebody
else is getting a grape.

00:09:59.330 --> 00:09:59.830
OK?

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:02.800
So there you see, we could be
very happy with our situation,

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:03.830
our station in life.

00:10:03.830 --> 00:10:05.470
We could be happy
with our salary

00:10:05.470 --> 00:10:07.820
until we find somebody
else is getting more,

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:12.600
and that contrast can make
us perfectly miserable.

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:17.550
So here, what's difficult
about comparisons

00:10:17.550 --> 00:10:19.660
is they can make us miserable.

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:21.720
They can increase
resentment and spite.

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:23.970
And we need to find our balance.

00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:28.290
And one way we do that is
to differentiate ourselves.

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:31.000
And the classic differentiation
is among siblings.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.020
So I talked about
siblings before.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.810
Often, siblings will have
very similar interests,

00:10:35.810 --> 00:10:37.310
but sometimes the
comparisons become

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:41.120
so aversive and grating that we
find ourselves differentiating

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:42.050
ourselves.

00:10:42.050 --> 00:10:46.540
So one sibling might be
really great at school.

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:47.460
Great at math.

00:10:47.460 --> 00:10:50.380
The other one's like, oh
well, I'm really an athlete,

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:51.590
or I'm the artist.

00:10:51.590 --> 00:10:54.210
And we find ourselves
differentiating ourselves.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:57.950
The most intense comparisons
happen with twins.

00:10:57.950 --> 00:10:59.940
And there have been a
number of twin studies

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:02.780
to really disentangle
the differences

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:07.710
between genetic and social
influences on how we develop.

00:11:07.710 --> 00:11:10.530
And one really interesting
thing about these twin studies

00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:12.680
is that you sometimes
see twins that

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:13.955
have been separated at birth.

00:11:13.955 --> 00:11:16.400
And they grow up in completely
different environments.

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:21.150
And they end up with
shockingly similar interests.

00:11:21.150 --> 00:11:23.950
Whereas often growing up, they
might have similar interests,

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:26.350
but they end up diverging.

00:11:26.350 --> 00:11:29.400
And here you find cases
where, yes, people sort of

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:32.130
balance this sort of
motivation, resentment,

00:11:32.130 --> 00:11:34.480
and find their balance,
you end applying things

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:36.625
like these twins,
separated at birth.

00:11:36.625 --> 00:11:38.500
They grew up in completely
separate families,

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.500
different religions,
different upbringings.

00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:44.350
But they ended up having
identical interests.

00:11:44.350 --> 00:11:46.560
They're both 100% into fitness.

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:49.825
And in fact, both of them
own bodybuilding gyms.

00:11:49.825 --> 00:11:51.700
And when they reconnected
in their 40's, they

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:55.220
were shocked at how
similar they actually were.

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:55.720
All right.

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:58.770
I'm going to turn it
over to Adam to continue.

