old, I ran a 10K race

00:12:13.170 --> 00:12:15.870
in 46 minutes, which is,
I think, pretty good.

00:12:15.870 --> 00:12:18.100
My brother ran it in under 44.

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:20.900
And so by the time I was 13,
I was no longer a runner,

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:22.450
but I was now a wrestler.

00:12:22.450 --> 00:12:25.030
So you can see how you
can change those things.

00:12:25.030 --> 00:12:28.800
What I want to turn to next is
another core topic of something

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:31.790
that we naturally
compare ourselves to.

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.780
When we think about, what
do other people have,

00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:35.404
we often think about
this one dimension

00:12:35.404 --> 00:12:36.890
that really matters a lot.

00:12:36.890 --> 00:12:38.340
And that's power.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:40.280
And one of the key
ideas that we develop

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:43.010
in this book-- and Maurice
and I have been doing research

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:47.060
on power and social
hierarchy for over 15 years,

00:12:47.060 --> 00:12:51.070
almost 20 years now-- is power
is a structural variable.

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:51.570
Right?

00:12:51.570 --> 00:12:54.114
When someone has power,
technically what that means

00:12:54.114 --> 00:12:55.655
is they control an
important resource

00:12:55.655 --> 00:12:58.880
that other people want, or
they have a higher level

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:00.410
of authority than other people.

00:13:00.410 --> 00:13:02.530
They can reward and
punish other people.

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:07.290
And that changes us in
some dramatic and intense

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:09.920
physiological and
neurological ways.

00:13:09.920 --> 00:13:12.300
But the key insight
that we develop

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:15.910
is that structural level
of power, why it matters,

00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:19.090
is because it creates a
psychological sense of power.

00:13:19.090 --> 00:13:21.380
And what really matters
more than anything else

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:23.090
is the psychological
sense of power.

00:13:23.090 --> 00:13:24.548
Now, I want to just
tel you briefly

00:13:24.548 --> 00:13:25.880
about a former student of mine.

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:27.270
She got her PhD at Kellogg.

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:29.407
Got a job talking at
Harvard Business School.

00:13:29.407 --> 00:13:30.990
And what happens
there is you come in,

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:33.630
and you do a 90 minute
presentation to the faculty,

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:37.430
and they have one job, which
is to try to tear you down.

00:13:37.430 --> 00:13:38.630
So they ask questions.

00:13:38.630 --> 00:13:40.790
They try to find logical flaws.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:42.930
They try to catch
your discrepancies

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:44.100
or inconsistencies.

00:13:44.100 --> 00:13:45.975
And she had a horrible
experience at Harvard,

00:13:45.975 --> 00:13:48.589
and felt really
deflated and devastated.

00:13:48.589 --> 00:13:50.630
A couple weeks later, she
got another job talking

00:13:50.630 --> 00:13:51.879
at London Business School.

00:13:51.879 --> 00:13:53.170
She really wanted to go London.

00:13:53.170 --> 00:13:54.070
She had family there.

00:13:54.070 --> 00:13:56.280
It was very exciting for her.

00:13:56.280 --> 00:13:58.100
And before her 90
minute presentation,

00:13:58.100 --> 00:14:00.557
they gave an opportunity to
spend some time by herself.

00:14:00.557 --> 00:14:02.390
And she said, you know
what I'm going to do,

00:14:02.390 --> 00:14:04.556
is I'm going to actually
use some of Adam's research

00:14:04.556 --> 00:14:05.570
and see if it helps me.

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:10.400
And she sat down for 15 minutes,
and she wrote a little essay

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.150
about a time when she had power.

00:14:12.150 --> 00:14:14.750
She really thought about this
experience when she had power,

00:14:14.750 --> 00:14:16.750
and she went into the
London Business Interview,

00:14:16.750 --> 00:14:19.890
and was in complete
control of the whole room.

00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:21.280
She was answering questions.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:22.810
She was building off ideas.

00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:24.094
And she got the job.

00:14:24.094 --> 00:14:25.760
She's tenured at
London Business School.

00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:27.130
She's very happy there.

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:30.040
And so we tried to
say, well, can we

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:32.530
take Jillian's
experience and test this?

00:14:32.530 --> 00:14:34.360
So what we did is
we went to France.

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:36.750
And there, people were
applying to business schools.

00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:39.680
And what they had set up was a
mock interview system for them,

00:14:39.680 --> 00:14:41.780
where they could go in
and have a mock interview

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:43.610
and get that experience.

00:14:43.610 --> 00:14:45.879
Now what they do is the
judges tell them at the end

00:14:45.879 --> 00:14:47.670
whether they would've
accepted them or not.

00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:49.380
So they get some
feedback about that,

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:50.672
and they get some coaching too.

00:14:50.672 --> 00:14:52.255
And we did a little
experiment, but we

00:14:52.255 --> 00:14:54.520
didn't tell the judges we
were doing an experiment.

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:56.550
So they had no idea.

00:14:56.550 --> 00:15:00.324
What we did is we randomly
asked a third of the people

00:15:00.324 --> 00:15:02.490
to think about a time when
they had high power, just

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:03.500
like Jillian.

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.625
We had third of the people
think about nothing.

00:15:05.625 --> 00:15:07.416
And then we had a third
of the people think

00:15:07.416 --> 00:15:08.660
about a time when
they had low power.

00:15:08.660 --> 00:15:09.160
Right?

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:11.790
Sort of, would that have a
negative psychological sense

00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:12.430
on them?

00:15:12.430 --> 00:15:14.980
And what you can see in this
data is a remarkable effect.

00:15:14.980 --> 00:15:17.770
The judges were told, on
average, to accept about 50%.

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:20.070
So say either you're in
or you're out about 50%

00:15:20.070 --> 00:15:20.786
of the time.

00:15:20.786 --> 00:15:22.660
And we can see here in
the control condition,

00:15:22.660 --> 00:15:24.020
that's exactly what they did.

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:26.090
But look what happened
when people would simply

00:15:26.090 --> 00:15:29.740
thought about experience they
had in which they lacked power.

00:15:29.740 --> 00:15:32.300
Their interview
performance plummeted.

00:15:32.300 --> 00:15:34.730
And now look what happened
in the high power condition.

00:15:34.730 --> 00:15:36.550
It rose up.

00:15:36.550 --> 00:15:38.464
And what this research
shows, and what

00:15:38.464 --> 00:15:40.380
studies that we've done
over the last 10 years

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:42.781
is that there's all this good
in this psychological sense

00:15:42.781 --> 00:15:43.280
of power.

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:45.220
It increases confidence.

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:47.060
It increases optimism.

00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:50.140
One of the researches done by a
professor at Berkeley out here

00:15:50.140 --> 00:15:53.720
showed that when you
give someone power,

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:55.250
their cortisol levels go down.

00:15:55.250 --> 00:15:56.166
Now, what is cortisol?

00:15:56.166 --> 00:15:57.110
It's a stress hormone.

00:15:57.110 --> 00:15:58.470
So you feel less stress.

00:15:58.470 --> 00:16:00.470
Other researchers have
looked at brain activity.

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:02.000
What gets active in the brain?

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.490
What's the approach and
agentic centers of the brain

00:16:04.490 --> 00:16:06.340
get activated when
you have power.

00:16:06.340 --> 00:16:08.230
So there's all
this good in power.

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:10.870
It makes the
impossible possible.

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:12.980
However, I want to do
another little experiment

00:16:12.980 --> 00:16:14.360
with everyone in this room.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:15.160
What I want you to
do is I want you

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:17.368
to hold up your dominant
hand with your index finger,

00:16:17.368 --> 00:16:18.800
just like this.

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:19.920
So everyone do this.

00:16:19.920 --> 00:16:22.240
And I want you, as
quickly as possible,

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:25.180
to draw a capital letter
E on your forehead

00:16:25.180 --> 00:16:26.760
with your index finger.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:28.060
Capital letter, forehead.

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:30.530
OK, good.

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:32.250
Now, it turns out
there's two ways

00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:34.380
that you can draw this
cap letter E. We did

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:36.890
a little experiment like this.

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:39.170
One of the ways you can
draw the capital letter E

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:41.460
is like Maurice.

00:16:41.460 --> 00:16:43.590
This is what we call
an other-oriented E.

00:16:43.590 --> 00:16:47.110
This is the correct E.
The only reason to do an E

00:16:47.110 --> 00:16:49.040
is so it looks like
an E to other people.

00:16:49.040 --> 00:16:51.530
Now, some of you, like
this gentleman right here,

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:53.635
drew what we would
call a backwards E,

00:16:53.635 --> 00:16:56.560
or a self-focused E. It
looks beautiful to me,

00:16:56.560 --> 00:16:58.417
but it's backwards
to other people.

00:16:58.417 --> 00:16:59.500
Now, why does this matter?

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:00.874
Well, we did a
little experiment.

00:17:00.874 --> 00:17:03.610
We brought undergraduates
from Northwestern University

00:17:03.610 --> 00:17:06.052
to experiment, and we
took one person and said,

00:17:06.052 --> 00:17:07.510
you're in the high
power condition.

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:09.839
That means you get to
control important resources.

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:12.310
You get to decide side
what another person gets.

00:17:12.310 --> 00:17:13.940
And we told someone
else, you're going

00:17:13.940 --> 00:17:16.000
to be in the low power
subordinate position.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.170
Someone else is going to
determine your rewards

00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:19.682
and what you get.

00:17:19.682 --> 00:17:21.390
And before they did
an activity together,

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:22.792
we separated them
in other rooms,

00:17:22.792 --> 00:17:24.500
and one of the things
we asked them to do

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:26.530
is draw a capital letter
E on the forehead.

00:17:26.530 --> 00:17:27.750
And look what we found.

00:17:27.750 --> 00:17:29.530
In the low power
condition, almost no one

00:17:29.530 --> 00:17:32.080
drew a self-focused E. It
was hovering around 10%.

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:34.205
But look what happened in
the high power condition.

00:17:34.205 --> 00:17:36.140
It tripled.

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:40.247
Over 30% percent of people
drew a self-focused E.

00:17:40.247 --> 00:17:41.330
So what does that tell us?

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:43.050
It tells us something
really important.

00:17:43.050 --> 00:17:45.840
Power reduces
perspective-taking.

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:48.120
And in fact, I just told you
about those brain studies

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:52.120
which show that power activates
the agentic parts of brain.

00:17:52.120 --> 00:17:55.200
It turns out it takes away this
other part of the brain called

00:17:55.200 --> 00:17:57.240
mentalizing network,
how we learn

00:17:57.240 --> 00:17:59.274
to understand other people.

00:17:59.274 --> 00:18:00.940
So what we need to
do is we need to find

00:18:00.940 --> 00:18:04.320
the right balance between
confidence, the good in power,

00:18:04.320 --> 00:18:09.190
and take away that self-focus,
so we end up with confidence

00:18:09.190 --> 00:18:10.440
and other-focus.

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:14.230
And I like to give a
metaphor of driving a car.

00:18:14.230 --> 00:18:17.160
And now, how do you get from
San Francisco to Mountain View?

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:18.200
Well, you need gas.

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:19.900
You need acceleration.

00:18:19.900 --> 00:18:21.760
But if you drive that
car without a steering

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:24.940
wheel-- not a Google self-driven
car, but a real person--

00:18:24.940 --> 00:18:27.560
then you would crash into
things along the way.

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:29.160
And so, we need
[INAUDIBLE] we need

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:32.060
to have acceleration, the
confidence, and a really

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:33.200
good steering wheel.

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:35.130
So we need gas and
a steering wheel.

00:18:35.130 --> 00:18:37.317
And one of the ways
that we need to do this

00:18:37.317 --> 00:18:39.400
is to understand something
that Maurice and I talk

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:41.680
about, which is
really important,

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:44.630
the power amplification effect.

00:18:44.630 --> 00:18:46.260
What is the power
amplification affect?

00:18:46.260 --> 00:18:51.450
Well, power when you whisper,
it can be heard like a shout.

00:18:51.450 --> 00:18:53.850
Now, I'll tell you just one
very quick experience I had.

00:18:53.850 --> 00:18:56.320
I was an assistant
professor at Kellogg,

00:18:56.320 --> 00:19:01.040
which means I have some power
over PhD doctoral students.

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:03.635
But I have less power than the
full-chaired professors who

00:19:03.635 --> 00:19:05.307
will vote on my tenure one day.

00:19:05.307 --> 00:19:07.140
And one day, I saw a
doctoral student, Gail,

00:19:07.140 --> 00:19:08.910
and I said, hey, Gail,
can you come by my office

00:19:08.910 --> 00:19:10.130
at 3 o'clock this afternoon.

00:19:10.130 --> 00:19:11.964
I need to talk to
you about something.

00:19:11.964 --> 00:19:14.310
Now, Gail walked into
my office like this.

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:16.420
She was crouched
down, she was wary,

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:18.252
she looked really
concerned, and she's

00:19:18.252 --> 00:19:19.460
like, well, what do you want?

00:19:19.460 --> 00:19:21.293
And I was like, it was
something so trivial,

00:19:21.293 --> 00:19:22.790
I can't even
remember what it was.

00:19:22.790 --> 00:19:25.060
And then she looked at me
sternly and said, never

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:26.365
do that again.

00:19:26.365 --> 00:19:27.620
I was like, do what?

00:19:27.620 --> 00:19:30.390
She said, never tell me you
need to talk to me, because it

00:19:30.390 --> 00:19:31.900
scared the hell out of me.

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:34.066
It's like, I was thinking,
did I do something wrong?

00:19:34.066 --> 00:19:34.880
Is he mad at me?

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:35.939
And I was like, OK, Gail?

00:19:35.939 --> 00:19:37.230
Maybe Gail's a little neurotic.

00:19:37.230 --> 00:19:37.490
You know?

00:19:37.490 --> 00:19:38.865
And I didn't think
much about it.

00:19:38.865 --> 00:19:41.900
And then the next day, I
get an email from my chair.

00:19:41.900 --> 00:19:44.020
And it says, hey, Adam,
can you come by office.

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:45.590
I really need to talk
to you this afternoon.

00:19:45.590 --> 00:19:46.964
And then I walked
into her office

00:19:46.964 --> 00:19:49.980
just like this, like, oh my god,
what's going on, what did I do?

00:19:49.980 --> 00:19:52.910
And then I realized this idea of
the power amplification effect.

00:19:52.910 --> 00:19:55.780
Now, there's a good in the
power amplification effect.

00:19:55.780 --> 00:19:57.550
When the powerful
express gratitude,

00:19:57.550 --> 00:19:59.415
it has a bigger impact.

00:19:59.415 --> 00:20:01.540
Ironically, my research
shows that the powerful are

00:20:01.540 --> 00:20:03.510
less likely to
express gratitude,

00:20:03.510 --> 00:20:04.920
but it does have
a bigger impact.

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:07.950
But small criticisms,
or even silence

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:10.390
get amplified and
become deafening

00:20:10.390 --> 00:20:11.750
when they're done by power.

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:13.160
Now, what's the solution here?

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:15.040
Well, it's really easy.

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:18.590
The first solution is
basically, tell them exactly why

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:19.930
you need to talk to them.

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:22.760
Or if it's too complicated
say, it's not a big deal.

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:23.690
Don't worry about it.

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:25.190
Or if it is a big
deal, you let them

00:20:25.190 --> 00:20:28.120
know it's a big deal, so
they can come prepared.

00:20:28.120 --> 00:20:32.630
Now, when we have high and
low power people in a group,

00:20:32.630 --> 00:20:34.010
now we have hierarchy.

00:20:34.010 --> 00:20:36.280
And I want to tell you,
the final little topic I'll

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:38.000
tell you about
today, and then we'll

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.380
answer some questions
is, when hierarchy wins,

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:42.550
and when it kills.

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:44.700
When hierarchy is good,
and when it's bad.

00:20:44.700 --> 00:20:48.140
Now, many years ago, when
Google got its start,

00:20:48.140 --> 00:20:50.070
they were like, we're engineers.

00:20:50.070 --> 00:20:51.900
We don't need any
managers, right?

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:53.410
We can do this on our own.

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:55.730
And it turned out there
was a lot of chaos.

00:20:55.730 --> 00:20:58.000
Some of you probably
know about Zappos

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:02.150
has turned this idea of
a holacracy this vision

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:04.390
of self-managed groups.

00:21:04.390 --> 00:21:08.940
And Tony Hsieh
introduced holacracy,

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:10.872
and he gave everyone an out.

00:21:10.872 --> 00:21:13.080
If you don't like your
experience in the first couple

00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:16.360
months, on this day in April,
tell us you want to quit,

00:21:16.360 --> 00:21:18.210
and we'll give you
three months severance.

00:21:18.210 --> 00:21:19.730
Now, Tony Hsieh
often gives people

00:21:19.730 --> 00:21:23.190
the opportunity to leave if
they're not happy at Zappos.

00:21:23.190 --> 00:21:27.330
And historically, about
2% of Zappos employees

00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:28.820
have taken the deal.

00:21:28.820 --> 00:21:33.570
On this day in April,
14% of the firm left.

00:21:33.570 --> 00:21:38.020
And what happened is it was too
hard to coordinate behavior.

00:21:38.020 --> 00:21:42.120
It was too difficult. And
so what a hierarchy provides

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:44.860
is it provides a
sense of coordination.

00:21:44.860 --> 00:21:47.360
Now to understand this, I want
to ask you a simple question.

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:51.090
Would you rather play a
game with your best friend

00:21:51.090 --> 00:21:52.719
or your boss?

00:21:52.719 --> 00:21:54.510
Now, most people would
say, my best friend.

00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:55.426
I love my best friend.

00:21:55.426 --> 00:21:56.670
We play games together.

00:21:56.670 --> 00:21:58.850
But I want to tell you
about this particular game.

00:21:58.850 --> 00:22:01.430
The game has two options.

00:22:01.430 --> 00:22:04.720
Option A is you get more
points, and more benefits,

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:06.670
more lottery tickets
than your partner.

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:08.830
And Option B, they get
double what you get.

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:09.330
Right?

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:10.720
So in option A, you get more.

00:22:10.720 --> 00:22:12.050
