00:27:03.550 --> 00:27:04.410
And people die.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:06.410
What's the single best
predictor of an infection

00:27:06.410 --> 00:27:08.050
getting to the main line?

00:27:08.050 --> 00:27:11.410
A doctor skipping
a checklist point.

00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:13.780
So what we can see
here is what they

00:27:13.780 --> 00:27:16.930
found is that nurses just didn't
feel comfortable speaking up.

00:27:16.930 --> 00:27:20.490
There's such a power status
gap between nurses and doctors

00:27:20.490 --> 00:27:23.780
that even when nurses saw the
doctor skip a crucial step,

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:27.220
they didn't force them to
go back and do that step.

00:27:27.220 --> 00:27:30.020
So the bad in
hierarchy is that it

00:27:30.020 --> 00:27:33.325
silences low power prospectives,
which can lead to disaster.

00:27:33.325 --> 00:27:34.980
Well, how do we
solve that problem?

00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:36.330
I'll tell you two examples.

00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:38.700
The first, let's go back
to the surgery example.

00:27:38.700 --> 00:27:41.080
What did Johns Hopkins
do to solve this problem?

00:27:41.080 --> 00:27:45.930
They gave the low power people
a little bit more power.

00:27:45.930 --> 00:27:47.199
How did they do that?

00:27:47.199 --> 00:27:48.990
They said, you know
what we're going to do?

00:27:48.990 --> 00:27:51.270
Nurses are in charge
of the checklist.

00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:53.570
We're going to give them
authority over the checklist,

00:27:53.570 --> 00:27:56.980
and that means they feel license
and legitimated to say, Doctor,

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:58.820
