00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:24.950
Now, as managers, there are a
few things that we can do this.

00:33:24.950 --> 00:33:29.050
We might describe
ranges of salaries

00:33:29.050 --> 00:33:30.990
that people are
getting, rather than

00:33:30.990 --> 00:33:33.380
making complete disclosure
of like, OK, here's how

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:35.760
much everybody else is getting.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:37.510
We see this at universities.

00:33:37.510 --> 00:33:40.560
Public universities
have to post salaries,

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:42.677
and that could make people
perfectly miserable.

00:33:42.677 --> 00:33:44.510
ADAM GALINSKY: Whereas
private schools, sort

00:33:44.510 --> 00:33:46.850
of like at Northwestern,
for example,

00:33:46.850 --> 00:33:49.770
they do the 25th percentile
of all associate professors

00:33:49.770 --> 00:33:51.720
in the Kellogg Business
School, and they also

00:33:51.720 --> 00:33:53.000
do the 75th percentile.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.310
So you can see sort of--
you can access were you,

00:33:55.310 --> 00:33:58.440
but I don't know what my
colleague is exactly getting.

00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:00.460
But your question's
also really important,

00:34:00.460 --> 00:34:02.140
because one of
the things that we

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:03.910
talk about it in the
chapter about gender

00:34:03.910 --> 00:34:06.960
is one of the single
best predictors

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:11.070
of reducing gender disparities
is having accurate information.

00:34:11.070 --> 00:34:13.040
And so the United
States, for example,

00:34:13.040 --> 00:34:15.770
had an executive order
of more transparency,

00:34:15.770 --> 00:34:17.449
and what were the
rates of promotion

00:34:17.449 --> 00:34:20.360
by gender, for example, and
they showed an increase.

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:24.469
Australia, what they did is they
decided that every company that

00:34:24.469 --> 00:34:27.100
reported to the
Australian Stock Exchange

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:31.010
had to release information,
both about promotion rates,

00:34:31.010 --> 00:34:33.170
but also how they went
about selecting people

00:34:33.170 --> 00:34:34.750
for different jobs
and promotions.

00:34:34.750 --> 00:34:39.010
And the percentage of women
went up 50% within two years

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:40.150
in management roles.

00:34:40.150 --> 00:34:42.799
And so one of the things
is we talk about is,

00:34:42.799 --> 00:34:44.590
transparency is actually
one of the hopeful

00:34:44.590 --> 00:34:49.113
things for reducing some of the
biases that exist in the world.

00:34:49.113 --> 00:34:50.779
Somehow, we didn't
answer your question.

00:34:50.779 --> 00:34:51.697
AUDIENCE: No, no, no.

00:34:51.697 --> 00:34:53.354
But it's a little bit
at odds, but you also

00:34:53.354 --> 00:34:54.978
said some kind of
transparency can make

00:34:54.978 --> 00:34:56.136
people perfectly miserable.

00:34:56.136 --> 00:34:56.969
ADAM GALINSKY: Yeah.

00:34:56.969 --> 00:34:58.469
MAURICE SCHWEITZER:
Yeah, miserable.

00:34:58.469 --> 00:35:04.970
So I think what's really report
is to have procedures in place.

00:35:04.970 --> 00:35:06.490
You want systematic procedures.

00:35:06.490 --> 00:35:09.150
You want a transparent system.

00:35:09.150 --> 00:35:11.190
And that's really important.

00:35:11.190 --> 00:35:14.400
And we want to think
about making broader

00:35:14.400 --> 00:35:16.920
structural changes,
there's are some problem,

00:35:16.920 --> 00:35:21.040
that transparency can be really
helpful in fixing problems.

00:35:21.040 --> 00:35:24.290
Individually, the transparency
of how much people

00:35:24.290 --> 00:35:26.247
are making, that could
make people just crazy.

00:35:26.247 --> 00:35:27.080
ADAM GALINSKY: Yeah.

00:35:27.080 --> 00:35:29.740
I think if I know what
every individual wants.

00:35:29.740 --> 00:35:33.470
But when Walmart was hit
with a class action suit, one

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:36.571
of things that happened was,
you might say, oh, women

00:35:36.571 --> 00:35:37.820
have less experience than men.

00:35:37.820 --> 00:35:39.540
That's why they're getting
paid-- it actually turned out

00:35:39.540 --> 00:35:40.870
women had more
experience than men,

00:35:40.870 --> 00:35:42.453
and they were still
getting paid less.

00:35:42.453 --> 00:35:43.920
And so, I don't
know exactly what

00:35:43.920 --> 00:35:46.250
this particular man or this
particular woman makes,

00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:47.870
but having some
assessment actually

00:35:47.870 --> 00:35:51.000
is really important in
that sense, in the same way

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.600
that I prefer Northwestern's
system of letting

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:55.960
us know the 25th and
75th percentile more

00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:59.730
than knowing what each colleague
in my department makes.

00:35:59.730 --> 00:36:05.060
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned that
praise from your higher-ups

00:36:05.060 --> 00:36:07.970
is more valued, but
it's more scarce.

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:11.641
So if it was more common, would
it still be valued as highly?

00:36:11.641 --> 00:36:13.640
ADAM GALINSKY: Yeah, so
that's a great question.

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:15.810
So I think that-- you
can just hold onto it.

00:36:20.640 --> 00:36:23.060
So we know that scarce
things are more valuable,

00:36:23.060 --> 00:36:25.340
and we also know that things
that come from high power

00:36:25.340 --> 00:36:27.050
people are more impactful.

00:36:27.050 --> 00:36:29.620
I think that there is one
element of that scarcity,

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:31.300
but I think that
some of the research

00:36:31.300 --> 00:36:35.910
shows that even high power
people who praise frequently,

00:36:35.910 --> 00:36:37.690
it still has this huge impact.

00:36:37.690 --> 00:36:40.970
It's especially impactful,
though, when high power people

00:36:40.970 --> 00:36:45.010
praise in a descriptive rather
than sort of a general way.

00:36:45.010 --> 00:36:48.430
Like saying, what you
did today was fantastic,

00:36:48.430 --> 00:36:51.730
is really great, rather like
oh, you're doing a great job.

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:54.380
And so the more descriptive--
feedback in general,

00:36:54.380 --> 00:36:56.670
the more descriptive it is,
the more valuable it is.

00:36:56.670 --> 00:36:59.430
And that amplification effect
gets even more amplified then

00:36:59.430 --> 00:37:00.490
in that case.

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:01.990
That's a great
question, because you

00:37:01.990 --> 00:37:04.880
have these competing variables,
scarcity and the high power

00:37:04.880 --> 00:37:06.140
aspect.

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:08.430
AUDIENCE: So given a
choice between cooperating

00:37:08.430 --> 00:37:10.130
and competing, this
sound very similar

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:12.330
to the classical
prisoner's dilemma, where

00:37:12.330 --> 00:37:15.580
lack of communication
is leading to a person

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:18.210
having to decide whether to
compete versus cooperate.

00:37:18.210 --> 00:37:21.540
Do you guys have any
idea of where or how

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:24.510
could be change a competition
into a cooperation?

00:37:24.510 --> 00:37:25.719
How do we enable that at all?

00:37:25.719 --> 00:37:26.760
MAURICE SCHWEITZER: Yeah.

00:37:26.760 --> 00:37:28.340
So there are a
couple of ideas here.

00:37:28.340 --> 00:37:31.330
One is, if we could think
about it structurally,

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:34.440
if we start cooperatively,
we signal our intentions,

00:37:34.440 --> 00:37:36.310
that can get us off
on the right foot.

00:37:36.310 --> 00:37:38.060
And in a lot of
our interactions,

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:40.680
we can do this by one on
one interactions with things

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:43.070
like non-task communication.

00:37:43.070 --> 00:37:45.740
So we don't get right
down to business.

00:37:45.740 --> 00:37:47.070
We chitchat first.

00:37:47.070 --> 00:37:50.900
We talk about sports, or the
weather, or something else.

00:37:50.900 --> 00:37:54.770
Now more broadly, if we have
a really competitive person,

00:37:54.770 --> 00:37:57.420
the best way to transform
a very competitive person

00:37:57.420 --> 00:38:01.850
into a cooperative person
is to put them on a team,

00:38:01.850 --> 00:38:04.020
and have them compete
with some other team.

00:38:04.020 --> 00:38:07.330
Or we think of one
organization, we're

00:38:07.330 --> 00:38:09.620
competing with some
other organization.

00:38:09.620 --> 00:38:13.240
And that can get somebody who's
really competitive, and now as

00:38:13.240 --> 00:38:15.800
soon as they say, oh no, we're
competing with somebody else,

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:18.567
now they're incredibly
intensely cooperative.

00:38:18.567 --> 00:38:20.900
ADAM GALINSKY: And I think
structurally, the other thing

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:23.690
that you can do is we can change
the very nature of the game.

00:38:23.690 --> 00:38:25.350
So one of our
favorite studies-- I

00:38:25.350 --> 00:38:27.440
know Maurice loves
this too-- is they

00:38:27.440 --> 00:38:30.030
took the prisoner's dilemma,
didn't change any aspect of it.

00:38:30.030 --> 00:38:32.564
So it's the same typical point.

00:38:32.564 --> 00:38:34.980
There's this conflict between
cooperation and competition,

00:38:34.980 --> 00:38:37.177
but the incentives lean
towards competition.

00:38:37.177 --> 00:38:38.760
And they just told
people, we're going

00:38:38.760 --> 00:38:40.170
to have you played game today.

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:41.824
It's called the
Wall Street game.

00:38:41.824 --> 00:38:43.240
And then people
just went straight

00:38:43.240 --> 00:38:44.427
to the competitive decision.

00:38:44.427 --> 00:38:46.260
Or they said we're going
to play game today.

00:38:46.260 --> 00:38:47.860
It's called the Community Game.

00:38:47.860 --> 00:38:50.161
And then people were much
more likely to choose

00:38:50.161 --> 00:38:51.660
the cooperative
choice, even thought

00:38:51.660 --> 00:38:53.184
the incentives hadn't changed.

00:38:53.184 --> 00:38:54.600
So some of the
ways that we can do

00:38:54.600 --> 00:38:58.150
is we can create that external
enemy, which is great.

00:38:58.150 --> 00:39:00.350
Other ways we can change
the nature of the task,

00:39:00.350 --> 00:39:03.790
and how we describe it, as
another example of doing that.

00:39:03.790 --> 00:39:06.430
And I think as Marie
said, one of the best ways

00:39:06.430 --> 00:39:08.020
is path dependence.

00:39:08.020 --> 00:39:09.300
Start with cooperation.

00:39:09.300 --> 00:39:12.260
If you go back to
Axelrod he came up

00:39:12.260 --> 00:39:16.290
with the famous-- the thing that
beats all other prison dilemma

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:16.856
games of all.

00:39:16.856 --> 00:39:18.310
It's called Tit For Tat.

00:39:18.310 --> 00:39:19.150
How's that work?

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:20.480
You start by cooperating.

00:39:20.480 --> 00:39:23.020
You cooperate as long as
the other person cooperates.

00:39:23.020 --> 00:39:25.310
As soon as they defect
for the first time,

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:26.870
you switch to defection.

00:39:26.870 --> 00:39:29.680
You keep defecting until
they go back to cooperation,

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:31.300
and then you go
back to cooperation.

00:39:31.300 --> 00:39:35.050
And that showed over-- it beat
every other possible strategy

00:39:35.050 --> 00:39:37.240
that existed in the world
in the prison's dilemma.

00:39:37.240 --> 00:39:40.270
So the most important
thing is start corporation,

00:39:40.270 --> 00:39:42.720
come with the right
labels, Community Game,

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:45.600
not Wall Street Game, and
come up with external threats

00:39:45.600 --> 00:39:48.580
that you can come
back together on.

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:50.580
AUDIENCE: So I'm
wondering about,

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:54.490
is there a clear distinction
between competing

00:39:54.490 --> 00:39:56.590
and being aggressive?

00:39:56.590 --> 00:40:02.640
And also maybe slightly
differently, have you

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:06.100
any insight into
say, the problem

00:40:06.100 --> 00:40:13.150
of social fairness towards
people who perhaps culturally

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:16.160
maybe-- like, the stereotypical
geeks, or whatever,

00:40:16.160 --> 00:40:19.910
who are less likely to compete.

00:40:19.910 --> 00:40:22.650
MAURICE SCHWEITZER: Yeah.

00:40:22.650 --> 00:40:25.990
Culturally, I talked
about fairness,

00:40:25.990 --> 00:40:28.430
the idea about
comparisons and fairness

00:40:28.430 --> 00:40:29.720
seemingly are hard-wired.

00:40:29.720 --> 00:40:33.710
So I showed you evidence
from cachupin monkeys.

00:40:33.710 --> 00:40:36.510
It's true here in
the United States,

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:38.800
and it's true internationally.

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:40.620
There's a fun-- there's
one parable, it's

00:40:40.620 --> 00:40:44.860
a Russian parable, about a
man who finds a lamp, rubs

00:40:44.860 --> 00:40:47.080
the lamp, a genie
appears, and says

00:40:47.080 --> 00:40:49.010
I can grant you
any wish you want.

00:40:49.010 --> 00:40:52.710
The condition is your
neighbor gets double.

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:54.292
So he paces back and forth.

00:40:54.292 --> 00:40:56.000
He thinks really hard
about this problem.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.170
And finally he says,
oh, I know what I want.

00:40:58.170 --> 00:40:59.753
I want you to poke
out one of my eyes.

00:41:01.950 --> 00:41:04.735
What I want to suggest is
that for many of us sort

00:41:04.735 --> 00:41:11.060
of very broadly, we have
this intense comparison

00:41:11.060 --> 00:41:12.710
and competitive drive.

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:16.740
Now, some of us aren't as
assertive or aggressive as we

00:41:16.740 --> 00:41:18.740
can be.

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:21.410
Adam's research was talking
about the power priming.

00:41:21.410 --> 00:41:24.150
When we think of a
time that we had power,

00:41:24.150 --> 00:41:26.740
we psychologically feel
like we have power,

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:31.490
and that gets us to approach
problems and be more assertive.

00:41:31.490 --> 00:41:33.240
ADAM GALINSKY: And I
think one of the ways

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:35.230
that we solve this
problem, we talk about this

00:41:35.230 --> 00:41:37.910
in the when and how to
start your engines chapter,

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:41.420
is how do you make an
ambitious first offer that

00:41:41.420 --> 00:41:43.270
also signals cooperation.

00:41:43.270 --> 00:41:45.580
So how do you anchor the
negotiation in your direction,

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:48.570
so you're being competitive,
but you're somehow signaling

00:41:48.570 --> 00:41:49.821
corporation to the other side?

00:41:49.821 --> 00:41:51.611
And there's actually
a technique that we've

00:41:51.611 --> 00:41:54.140
created that's incredibly
effective, which is what I do,

00:41:54.140 --> 00:41:57.120
is I offer you a
choice among offers.

00:41:57.120 --> 00:41:59.860
So I say, look, here's
two or three offers.

00:41:59.860 --> 00:42:01.320
I'm indifferent between them.

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:03.010
You pick the one
that's best for you,

00:42:03.010 --> 00:42:04.385
and we can make
a deal right now.

00:42:04.385 --> 00:42:07.280
So let's say you're
going with cars.

00:42:07.280 --> 00:42:08.790
You're like, I can
give you this car

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:10.895
in this color with this mileage.

00:42:10.895 --> 00:42:11.830
You know, a used car.

00:42:11.830 --> 00:42:14.080
Or I could give you this
car in a different color

00:42:14.080 --> 00:42:15.489
with some different mileage.

00:42:15.489 --> 00:42:18.030
And I'm going to give you the
same price for both those cars.

00:42:18.030 --> 00:42:19.696
You just pick the one
you like the most.

00:42:19.696 --> 00:42:22.590
Now, we may be anchoring the
negotiation in our favor.

00:42:22.590 --> 00:42:24.400
But because we're
giving you a choice,

00:42:24.400 --> 00:42:26.000
we're signaling corporation.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:28.450
And so our research has
shown that people walk out

00:42:28.450 --> 00:42:31.456
being like, that was a
cooperative flexible person.

00:42:31.456 --> 00:42:32.830
But we showed that
by doing that,

00:42:32.830 --> 00:42:34.204
I actually got a
much better deal

00:42:34.204 --> 00:42:37.490
than I would have if I had
just given you one offer.

00:42:37.490 --> 00:42:41.250
MAURICE SCHWEITZER: So
intensity will be different.

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:43.750
I don't want to suggest that
the cultural differences aren't

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:44.307
important.

00:42:44.307 --> 00:42:46.140
Our cultural differences
are very important,

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:49.070
and they will guide
very different behavior,

00:42:49.070 --> 00:42:52.720
like Adam's research talking
about the Himalayan Mountains

00:42:52.720 --> 00:42:53.740
expedition.

00:42:53.740 --> 00:42:58.140
So culture matters for sure.

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:00.640
What I am saying is that
a lot of these principles

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:03.180
are so profound--
that is, they're

00:43:03.180 --> 00:43:07.200
hard-wired into the architecture
of our brains-- all of us

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:08.940
engage in comparisons.

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:11.220
Now, some of us
are crazy about it.

00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:13.224
So some of us check
Facebook all the time.

00:43:13.224 --> 00:43:15.265
We're constantly monitoring
what people are doing

00:43:15.265 --> 00:43:16.640
and how they're doing it.

00:43:16.640 --> 00:43:19.240
And some of us kind of
skate through life caring

00:43:19.240 --> 00:43:20.510
less about it.

00:43:20.510 --> 00:43:23.490
What I am suggesting is that
all of us care about it,

00:43:23.490 --> 00:43:25.390
and these comparisons
give us meaning.

00:43:25.390 --> 00:43:28.890
We can't get away from them,
and so they're hard-wired.

00:43:28.890 --> 00:43:32.090
But there are definitely
individual differences

00:43:32.090 --> 00:43:33.530
and cultural differences.

00:43:33.530 --> 00:43:35.050
ADAM GALINSKY: Yeah, I think
two just other quick things

00:43:35.050 --> 00:43:35.800
to say about that.

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:39.930
One is what we compare is going
to depend partially on culture.

00:43:39.930 --> 00:43:42.890
So in some cultures,
the car that you drive

00:43:42.890 --> 00:43:45.800
has a huge impact on
how people treat you,

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:48.860
and I want to have a better
car than my neighbor,

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:50.740
and so the car is
a big distinction.

00:43:50.740 --> 00:43:52.950
Other people, it might
be what technology,

00:43:52.950 --> 00:43:54.090
like what phone you have.

00:43:54.090 --> 00:43:57.360
Do you the latest greatest
Android phone, for example?

00:43:57.360 --> 00:43:58.430
Not the iPhone.

00:43:58.430 --> 00:44:02.610
But you know, things like that
can make a big difference.

00:44:02.610 --> 00:44:07.260
So context and culture
really alter those dynamics.

00:44:07.260 --> 00:44:09.890
And I think one of the
things, like with power,

00:44:09.890 --> 00:44:12.410
is power exists
in every society,

00:44:12.410 --> 00:44:15.620
but it has some sort of
slightly different effects,

00:44:15.620 --> 00:44:16.800
depending on the society.

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:18.970
So how those patterns
of deference play out,

00:44:18.970 --> 00:44:20.360
and when they matter.

00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:23.390
And for example, the
power amplification effect

00:44:23.390 --> 00:44:25.840
is even stronger in
some East Asian cultures

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:27.530
than it is an American cultures.

00:44:27.530 --> 00:44:31.489
Criticism by boss is so painful
in some cultures, stories

00:44:31.489 --> 00:44:33.405
of people committing
suicide just because they

00:44:33.405 --> 00:44:34.950
were criticized in a meeting.

00:44:34.950 --> 00:44:37.050
That seems hard to
believe from our culture.

00:44:37.050 --> 00:44:38.640
Even though we're going
to have the same impact,

00:44:38.640 --> 00:44:40.139
the intensity is
going to be greater

00:44:40.139 --> 00:44:41.530
in some cultures than others.

00:44:41.530 --> 00:44:43.265
So that's great question.

00:44:43.265 --> 00:44:44.390
I learned that from Sechin.

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:45.598
That's a great question, sir.

00:44:45.598 --> 00:44:49.092
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
encourage people to ask.

00:44:49.092 --> 00:44:51.300
AUDIENCE: As you both are
business school professors,

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:54.300
do you also infer
changes to how people

00:44:54.300 --> 00:44:55.550
should manage their companies?

00:44:55.550 --> 00:44:57.320
How HR systems should be set up?

00:44:57.320 --> 00:44:59.610
Performance, evaluation,
things like that?

00:44:59.610 --> 00:45:01.699
Do you transfer these findings?

00:45:01.699 --> 00:45:02.740
MAURICE SCHWEITZER: Yeah.

00:45:02.740 --> 00:45:05.880
I mean, interesting.

00:45:05.880 --> 00:45:09.200
We're actually working on
a piece right now talking

00:45:09.200 --> 00:45:12.260
about diversity
training programs.

00:45:12.260 --> 00:45:15.340
A lot of diversity training
programs, for example, fail.

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:18.430
So simply raising awareness
sometimes isn't enough.

00:45:18.430 --> 00:45:21.780
We need to think about
more systematic approaches

00:45:21.780 --> 00:45:24.070
for mentoring and so on.

00:45:24.070 --> 00:45:28.110
When it comes to the kind of
feedback that we give people,

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:30.640
so the feedback systems
should be different.

00:45:30.640 --> 00:45:32.640
When it comes to the
way we share information

00:45:32.640 --> 00:45:35.030
about salary information.

00:45:35.030 --> 00:45:39.530
So they all have direct
applications for these ideas,

00:45:39.530 --> 00:45:44.907
and they should guide manageable
action and corporate policy.

00:45:44.907 --> 00:45:47.490
ADAM GALINSKY: And I also think
that finding the right balance

00:45:47.490 --> 00:45:49.073
with hierarchy is
so important, right?

00:45:49.073 --> 00:45:52.114
We know the absence of
hierarchy leads to chaos.

00:45:52.114 --> 00:45:54.530
And one of the things-- we
were giving this talk yesterday

00:45:54.530 --> 00:45:55.720
at Zillow, and
someone pointed out

00:45:55.720 --> 00:45:57.160
that a friend
worked at a company

00:45:57.160 --> 00:45:58.868
where they tried not
having any managers.

00:45:58.868 --> 00:46:00.390
And what it really
means is nobody

00:46:00.390 --> 00:46:02.361
does the jobs that
nobody wants to do.

00:46:02.361 --> 00:46:02.860
Right?

00:46:02.860 --> 00:46:05.340
Because no one does
it because-- and so

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:08.070
you need someone who says,
OK, you have to do this job.

00:46:08.070 --> 00:46:09.224
We have to get this done.

00:46:09.224 --> 00:46:10.640
You need some
[INAUDIBLE] control,

00:46:10.640 --> 00:46:12.890
but you don't want to
silence low power voices

00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:14.220
and prevent innovation.

00:46:14.220 --> 00:46:16.220
And so you need to
find some that balance

00:46:16.220 --> 00:46:18.410
between coordination and
silencing low voices,

00:46:18.410 --> 00:46:19.676
and what's that level?

00:46:19.676 --> 00:46:20.800
I'm not a fan of holacracy.

00:46:20.800 --> 00:46:23.300
I don't think that's a very
good people management strategy.

00:46:23.300 --> 00:46:25.990
I think it'll probably
fail in the long-term.

00:46:25.990 --> 00:46:29.620
Because just as Google needed
managers, not just engineers,

00:46:29.620 --> 00:46:31.820
is that we need to
have some sort of sense

00:46:31.820 --> 00:46:35.590
of coordination mechanisms and
devices that get into play.

00:46:35.590 --> 00:46:38.730
But I think one of the things
that HR need to recognize

00:46:38.730 --> 00:46:40.760
is, how do you find
the right balance?

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:42.510
Another example,
just really briefly,

00:46:42.510 --> 00:46:45.590
is team awards versus
individual awards.

00:46:45.590 --> 00:46:46.180
Right?

00:46:46.180 --> 00:46:48.660
And the research shows, if you
just have individual awards,

00:46:48.660 --> 00:46:50.050
you get competitive behavior.

00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:52.990
If you just have team rewards,
you get social loafing.

00:46:52.990 --> 00:46:54.612
So you need to have
some combination.

00:46:54.612 --> 00:46:55.820
What's the exact combination?

00:46:55.820 --> 00:46:57.340
That's a tougher
question to answer.

00:46:57.340 --> 00:47:00.660
But some combination of rewards
that tie people together,

00:47:00.660 --> 00:47:02.490
but still motivate
individual performance.

00:47:02.490 --> 00:47:03.823
You're going to ask a follow-up.

00:47:03.823 --> 00:47:06.532
AUDIENCE: Do you a company that
gets the hierarchy thing right?

00:47:06.532 --> 00:47:08.740
ADAM GALINSKY: Well, I have
to say Google, of course,

00:47:08.740 --> 00:47:09.570
gets it perfectly.

00:47:09.570 --> 00:47:11.220
But it's uh--

00:47:11.220 --> 00:47:12.912
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:12.912 --> 00:47:15.530
MAURICE SCHWEITZER:
You don't think so.

00:47:15.530 --> 00:47:18.700
ADAM GALINSKY: I think
there's-- I mean,

00:47:18.700 --> 00:47:21.410
I think a lot of successful
companies are doing this.

00:47:21.410 --> 00:47:23.344
And I think a lot of
Silicon Valley companies

00:47:23.344 --> 00:47:25.760
have been successful in trying
to find that right balance.

00:47:25.760 --> 00:47:28.610
And I think some of them-- I
think like Zappos have tipped

00:47:28.610 --> 00:47:30.340
too far towards one direction.

00:47:30.340 --> 00:47:33.360
We just spoke at
Microsoft the other day.

00:47:33.360 --> 00:47:35.890
And I think some people felt
Microsoft might have tipped

00:47:35.890 --> 00:47:38.550
too far towards
hierarchy level, and too

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:40.890
much sort of individual
awards and competitions

00:47:40.890 --> 00:47:41.590
around that too.

00:47:41.590 --> 00:47:43.820
And so it's tough to
find that balance.

00:47:43.820 --> 00:47:45.361
MAURICE SCHWEITZER:
Let me just offer

00:47:45.361 --> 00:47:48.070
one other example
to sort of suggest

00:47:48.070 --> 00:47:50.030
that it's a constant struggle.

00:47:50.030 --> 00:47:52.490
If you look at the
military, the military's

00:47:52.490 --> 00:47:55.380
this classic
hierarchical structure.

00:47:55.380 --> 00:47:57.030
So we have a lot
of different ranks,

00:47:57.030 --> 00:47:59.120
and you have to follow orders.

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:04.050
And for many tasks that just
require people to do things

00:48:04.050 --> 00:48:07.110
that they don't want to do,
you need strong hierarchy

00:48:07.110 --> 00:48:10.910
that moves people in a
very coordinated way.

00:48:10.910 --> 00:48:15.360
And yet, for new challenges, you
think about the Special Forces.

00:48:15.360 --> 00:48:19.010
And the Special Forces, they've
broken down the hierarchy.

00:48:19.010 --> 00:48:20.530
And there, it's much flatter.

00:48:20.530 --> 00:48:21.780
You have very different roles.

00:48:21.780 --> 00:48:23.280
People can speak
back to their boss.

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:25.140
They can disagree.

00:48:25.140 --> 00:48:27.470
And here within
same organization,

00:48:27.470 --> 00:48:30.340
they've created very different
hierarchical structures

00:48:30.340 --> 00:48:32.910
to tackle different
kinds of problems.

00:48:32.910 --> 00:48:37.262
So the nature of the task
needs to fit the hierarchy.

00:48:37.262 --> 00:48:38.720
ADAM GALINSKY: And
notice something

00:48:38.720 --> 00:48:40.820
else about the Special
Forces is, they

00:48:40.820 --> 00:48:42.611
tend to be smaller groups.

00:48:42.611 --> 00:48:43.110
Right?

00:48:43.110 --> 00:48:45.930
As these groups get bigger,
you need a little bit more,

00:48:45.930 --> 00:48:48.010
some type of
mechanisms of control.

00:48:48.010 --> 00:48:50.340
But when you're going in,
and you're a 20 person team,

00:48:50.340 --> 00:48:53.050
it's a little bit easier for
you to handle those situations.

00:48:53.050 --> 00:48:57.090
And so, I think that's
another great example of it.

00:48:57.090 --> 00:48:58.475
AUDIENCE: So I have a question.

00:48:58.475 --> 00:49:00.890
A few months, I read Adam
Grant's book, "Give and Take,"

00:49:00.890 --> 00:49:03.070
which I assume you both
are somewhat familiar with.

00:49:03.070 --> 00:49:05.720
Basically, it says there are
givers, takers, and matchers.

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:07.616
And if I'm
remembering correctly,

00:49:07.616 --> 00:49:09.240
when interacting with
a quote, unquote,

00:49:09.240 --> 00:49:12.140
"taker," the people who
are really successful

00:49:12.140 --> 00:49:15.010
are those who basically
stop giving to that person

00:49:15.010 --> 00:49:17.110
until they become a
matcher, so to speak.

00:49:17.110 --> 00:49:19.340
So in applying it
to this, I'm curious

00:49:19.340 --> 00:49:21.803
if-- assuming that you can't
create an external enemy

00:49:21.803 --> 00:49:25.160
or anything, if someone is
a super competitive person,

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:28.610
isn't it better to adjust and to
also be pretty competitive back

00:49:28.610 --> 00:49:30.910
to that person until
they become a little bit

00:49:30.910 --> 00:49:32.036
more middle of the road?

00:49:32.036 --> 00:49:34.160
ADAM GALINSKY: That's
exactly the tit for tat thing

00:49:34.160 --> 00:49:35.530
that I mentioned that.

00:49:35.530 --> 00:49:38.240
The single best strategy
for the prisoner's dilemma

00:49:38.240 --> 00:49:40.390
is signal corporation,
cooperate,

00:49:40.390 --> 00:49:42.890
if they compete, compete
with them until they're

00:49:42.890 --> 00:49:44.410
willing to go back
to cooperation,

00:49:44.410 --> 00:49:45.590
and then you switch back.

00:49:45.590 --> 00:49:46.910
And I think that's right.

00:49:46.910 --> 00:49:49.450
I think that the one
thing that really, I

00:49:49.450 --> 00:49:52.723
think, changes the very
essence-- and Adam Grant's book

00:49:52.723 --> 00:49:53.340
is great.

00:49:53.340 --> 00:49:55.952
And obviously, he's a colleague
of Maurice's, and we know him

00:49:55.952 --> 00:49:56.910
very well.

00:49:56.910 --> 00:49:58.740
Wrote a blurb for the book.

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:01.760
But I think, really, what our
book is fundamentally different

00:50:01.760 --> 00:50:04.007
about this is this
idea that we don't just

00:50:04.007 --> 00:50:05.590
have givers, and
takers, and matchers,

00:50:05.590 --> 00:50:08.220
it's that in every
relationship, there's

00:50:08.220 --> 00:50:10.510
this tension between
cooperation and competition.

00:50:10.510 --> 00:50:12.285
And we have to be aware of that.

00:50:12.285 --> 00:50:13.660
And we have to
ask ourselves, how

00:50:13.660 --> 00:50:14.800
do we find the right balance?

00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:16.216
So I'll just give
you one example.

00:50:16.216 --> 00:50:19.340
Maurice does is great thing in
his negotiations class, where

00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:20.640
you negotiate every week.

00:50:20.640 --> 00:50:22.510
You have to write
down little thoughts

00:50:22.510 --> 00:50:23.719
about like, your negotiation.

00:50:23.719 --> 00:50:25.426
And then about half
way through the class

00:50:25.426 --> 00:50:26.930
he says, OK, what
I want you to do

00:50:26.930 --> 00:50:29.345
is I want you to go back and
read your first five or six

00:50:29.345 --> 00:50:29.845
weeks.

00:50:29.845 --> 00:50:31.910
And I want you to ask
yourself this question,

00:50:31.910 --> 00:50:34.470
am I cooperating too
much, and am I getting

00:50:34.470 --> 00:50:36.530
exploited in the negotiations?

00:50:36.530 --> 00:50:38.450
Am I competing too
much consistently,

00:50:38.450 --> 00:50:41.590
so maybe I'm killing joint
gain and expanding the pie?

00:50:41.590 --> 00:50:43.430
Or am I finding
the right balance.

00:50:43.430 --> 00:50:45.890
If I'm over here, how
can I get over here?

00:50:45.890 --> 00:50:46.390
Right?

00:50:46.390 --> 00:50:49.090
If I'm too far this way,
how do I get back to here?

00:50:49.090 --> 00:50:51.970
And I think that reflection
is really important.

00:50:51.970 --> 00:50:54.110
A lot of it's about this
sort of self-understanding

00:50:54.110 --> 00:50:57.180
of that tension, and trying
to find the right path.

00:50:57.180 --> 00:50:59.950
And I see Sechin just
looked at his watch,

00:50:59.950 --> 00:51:02.260
so I think we have time
for one more question.

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:04.140
Yeah?

00:51:04.140 --> 00:51:07.220
AUDIENCE: So I'm seeing
a lot of discussion

00:51:07.220 --> 00:51:09.740
where it leads to
like, a 50-50 harmony.

00:51:09.740 --> 00:51:17.236
But how does the competition
versus cooperation-- there

00:51:17.236 --> 00:51:21.512
we go-- affect in terms
of like innovation?

00:51:21.512 --> 00:51:23.470
I feel like we don't talk
about the innovation.

00:51:23.470 --> 00:51:24.760
We talk more about like,
just keeping the peace.

00:51:24.760 --> 00:51:26.760
ADAM GALINSKY: Well, I've
spoken 53% of the time,

00:51:26.760 --> 00:51:28.385
so I'm going to let
Maurice answer that

00:51:28.385 --> 00:51:29.766
question to make it more 50-50.

00:51:29.766 --> 00:51:31.640
MAURICE SCHWEITZER:
Well, I mean, it's funny,

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:34.950
because you
mentioned innovation.

00:51:34.950 --> 00:51:39.610
With innovation, that's where
we want to break down hierarchy

00:51:39.610 --> 00:51:41.010
to sort of free these ideas.

00:51:41.010 --> 00:51:45.490
And Adam was talking
about examples from IDO,

00:51:45.490 --> 00:51:48.700
where when we're
generating ideas,

00:51:48.700 --> 00:51:51.220
we want to remove criticism.

00:51:51.220 --> 00:51:52.680
Now, here's one idea.

00:51:52.680 --> 00:51:54.680
Ironically, we actually
want some rules.

00:51:54.680 --> 00:51:58.620
We want rules about no
interruptions, no criticism.

00:51:58.620 --> 00:52:00.050
With those rules,
we can actually

00:52:00.050 --> 00:52:05.660
set ourselves freer to explore
ideas to be more creative.

00:52:05.660 --> 00:52:08.360
And we want to separate
the idea creation stage

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:10.702
from the idea criticism stage.

00:52:10.702 --> 00:52:12.910
ADAM GALINSKY: And The New
York City Fire Department,

00:52:12.910 --> 00:52:15.380
for example, when they're
trying to implement or come up

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:17.176
with new ways of
fighting fires, they

00:52:17.176 --> 00:52:19.050
want people from all
different ranks and part

00:52:19.050 --> 00:52:21.950
of the organization, when they
come into those conversations,

00:52:21.950 --> 00:52:23.742
they're not allowed to
wear their uniforms.

00:52:23.742 --> 00:52:25.283
Because all of a
sudden, rank becomes

00:52:25.283 --> 00:52:27.180
such a big, compelling
force, and we really

00:52:27.180 --> 00:52:30.260
want people to feel
comfortable sharing ideas.

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:31.910
But the single
greatest way for you

00:52:31.910 --> 00:52:33.826
to find this right balance
between corporation

00:52:33.826 --> 00:52:36.691
and competition
and innovation is

00:52:36.691 --> 00:52:38.315
buying three or four
copies of the book

00:52:38.315 --> 00:52:39.635
and getting us to sign it.

00:52:39.635 --> 00:52:42.200
So that's really the key
thing to the whole thing.

00:52:42.200 --> 00:52:44.415
Well, thank you guys
so much for coming out.

00:52:44.415 --> 00:52:46.290
We're happy to sign the
books and everything.

00:52:46.290 --> 00:52:49.340
[APPLAUSE]

